Today’s senseless murder of Charlie Kirk on the UVU campus and the high school shooting outside of Denver shortly thereafter represent the 47th and 48th campus shootings this year. As a former District Attorney, I've seen up close the impacts of gun violence on victims and their families, and every single senseless act leaves me with a sick and hollow feeling in the pit of my stomach. Whether in the exercise of free speech, or in worshipping, or in attending school, Americans have a right to live free from violence. Beyond today's breaking news stories are many more families that have been or will be impacted by gun violence today - an average of one death every eleven minutes. My prayers are with Charlie Kirk’s young family and every single family impacted by gun violence. It must end.

Today I met Belarusian political activist Siarhei Tsikhanouski. My full statement:

Today, I met with @tsikhanouski_s - just three months after his release from political imprisonment in Belarus. This is a man who just 100 days ago was living in complete solitary confinement, in horrific conditions, after being illegally detained.  His bravery and resilience should be an example to us all.

As Belarus Caucus Co-Chair, I have worked for more than 5 years to help facilitate the release of Siarhei and the more than 1,300 political prisoners who remain behind bars. Siarhei is an example of courage, conviction, determination, and more than anything else – love of his homeland.  He has consistently stood up in defense of the values he and the entire Free Belarus movement support. I know we have Siarhei’s support as we continue to advocate for those who remain behind bars.

While Siarhei was imprisoned, his wife, Sviatlana, advocated on his behalf and on behalf of all Belarusians who detest the brutal Lukashenka regime. In March 2020, as Chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe, Sviatlana testified before the Subcommittee in her first public interaction with the United States government. Then, and now, she continues the fight for a Free Belarus. I am so grateful that Siarhei has now rejoined her on this journey.

A strong U.S.-Ukraine relationship is critical to ensuring a long-lasting and durable peace in Ukraine. This long-awaited critical minerals deal is an important aspect of our bilateral relationship and an example of how, if we work together, we can support Ukraine’s sovereignty and keep the transatlantic alliance safe from future Russian aggression.
 
While this agreement is constructive and a good example of working with Ukraine, it does not supplant our commitment to supporting Ukraine’s sovereignty and territorial integrity, a commitment which goes back to the 1994 Budapest Memorandum and the more recently established Ukraine Defense Contact Group with an alliance of more than 50 countries.
 
Unfortunately, the Trump-led negotiations to end the war have appeased the Kremlin, isolated Ukraine, and brought tension to our transatlantic relationship. This is no way to treat our allies and our friends, let alone the Kremlin. Nor is it a practical solution for finding a lasting ceasefire and peace deal which must include credible security guarantees.
 
The Trump administration must move forward with a clear sense of vision and purpose to end this conflict and with the acknowledgement that Vladimir Putin is the aggressor and the impediment to peace. Any alternative will leave the Kremlin stronger and both Ukraine and the transatlantic alliance in a weaker position than before.

At the same time, we must also acknowledge that there are prominent voices in our country that, in my belief, have failed to live up to the ideals and values that underpin the Ukrainian-American relationship.
I wholeheartedly support this assistance and stand with the Ukrainian people as they continue to fight for their freedom.

In the spirit of Ukraine’s resilience, the United States and Congress has provided more than $180 billion in assistance to Ukraine, and we have marshaled a coalition of more than 50 allies in support of Ukraine’s efforts.

Over the past three years, the Ukrainian military has repelled the worst of Russia’s invasion, defended a free and democratic Ukraine, and held the Russian military and government accountable for its war of aggression.

Today, we mark three years since the beginning of Russia’s full-scale invasion of Ukraine, a day to reflect on the strength and resolve of the Ukrainian people who have been the defenders of freedom and democracy around the world since the war began.
